Introduction¶

This is a Portfolio Project from 100 Days of Code: The Complete Python Pro Bootcamp.

Since Jan. 1, 2015, The Washington Post has been compiling a database of every fatal shooting in the US by a police officer in the line of duty.

While there are many challenges regarding data collection and reporting, The Washington Post has been tracking more than a dozen details about each killing. This includes the race, age and gender of the deceased, whether the person was armed, and whether the victim was experiencing a mental-health crisis. The Washington Post has gathered this supplemental information from law enforcement websites, local new reports, social media, and by monitoring independent databases such as "Killed by police" and "Fatal Encounters". The Post has also conducted additional reporting in many cases.

There are 4 additional datasets: US census data on poverty rate, high school graduation rate, median household income, and racial demographics. Source of census data.

Chart the Poverty Rate in each US State¶

To start with we're going to create a bar chart displaying average poverty rates across all the US states.

In [ ]:
poverty_rate_by_state = df_pct_poverty.groupby('Geographic Area', as_index=False).agg({'poverty_rate': pd.Series.mean})
In [ ]:
poverty_rate_by_state = poverty_rate_by_state.sort_values('poverty_rate', ascending=False)
In [ ]:
bar = px.bar(y=poverty_rate_by_state['poverty_rate'],
               x=poverty_rate_by_state['Geographic Area'],
               title='Average Poverty Rate by US State',
               color=poverty_rate_by_state['poverty_rate'],
               color_continuous_scale='Brwnyl')

bar.update_layout(xaxis_title='US State', yaxis_title='Poverty Rate', coloraxis_showscale=False)

bar.show()
bar.write_html('1Average_poverty_rate_by_us_state.html')

The state with the highest poverty rate is Mississippi (MS) at almost 27%, followed by Arizona (AZ) at 25.6%. The lowest poverty rate is in the state of New Jersey (NJ) with only 8.2%.

However, we need to investigate it further to see if there's a correlation between these two measures across all of the states.

Visualise the Relationship between Poverty Rates and High School Graduation Rates¶

To analyse the relationship between poverty rates and high school graduation rates we're going to create a line chart with two y-axes to show if the rations of poverty and high school graduation move together.

In [ ]:

In [ ]:

plt.title('Relationship between Poverty Rates and High School Graduation Rates', fontsize=14)

ax2.set_ylabel('HS Graduation Rate', color='teal', fontsize=12)

Text(0, 0.5, 'HS Graduation Rate')

We can observe that in most states when the poverty rate goes up, the high school graduation rate goes down and vice versa.

Now we're going to use a Seaborn .jointplot() with a Kernel Density Estimate (KDE) and/or scatter plot to visualise the same relationship¶

In [ ]:

jplot.set_axis_labels('Poverty Rate (%)', 'High School Graduation Rate (%)', fontsize=14)
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)

We can observe the same pattern, when the high school graduation rate decreases the poverty rate increases.

Create a Bar Chart with Subsections Showing the Racial Makeup of Each US State¶

We're going to visualise the share of the white, black, hispanic, asian and native american population in each US State using a bar chart with sub sections. In order to do that we need to aggregate the data by summing the shares for each racial group within each state. After that we have to normalize the data to ensure the sum of the racial shares per state equals 100%.

In [ ]:
df_state_sum = df_share_race_city.drop('City', axis='columns')
In [ ]:
df_state_sum = df_state_sum.groupby('Geographic area').sum().reset_index()
In [ ]:
df_state_sum[['share_white', 'share_black', 'share_native_american', 'share_asian', 'share_hispanic']] = \
    df_state_sum[['share_white', 'share_black', 'share_native_american', 'share_asian', 'share_hispanic']].div(
        df_state_sum[['share_white', 'share_black', 'share_native_american', 'share_asian', 'share_hispanic']].sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100
In [ ]:
df_melted = df_state_sum.melt(id_vars=['Geographic area'],
                    value_vars=['share_white', 'share_black', 'share_native_american', 'share_asian', 'share_hispanic'],
                    var_name='Race',
                    value_name='Racial_share')
In [ ]:
df_melted['Race'] = df_melted['Race'].str.replace('share_', '')
In [ ]:
color_sequence = px.colors.sequential.Mint

fig = px.bar(df_melted, y="Racial_share", x="Geographic area", color=df_melted.Race,
               title='Racial Makeup of Each US State',
             color_discrete_sequence=color_sequence)

fig.update_layout(xaxis_title='State',
                  yaxis_title='Racial Share',
                  coloraxis_showscale=False
                  )

fig.show()
fig.write_html('3Racial_makeup_of_each_state.html')

Vermont (VT) has the highest share of white population - 96.5%. The highest share of black population is in Washington, D.C. with 49.6%. The biggest number (almost 48%) of Native Americans lives in Alaska (AK). The biggest Asian population can be found in Hawaii (HI) - 36%. Hispanic population is the highest in New Mexico (NM) with 35.7%.

Overall we can see that the most predominant race in most of the states is white.

Let's create a separate KDE plot for each race and see if there is a difference between the distributions.

In [ ]:
df_races = df_fatalities.dropna(subset=['race'])
In [ ]:
races = df_races['race'].unique()
In [ ]:
num_plots = len(races)
palette = sns.color_palette("YlGnBu", num_plots)
In [ ]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(18, 12), sharex=True, sharey=True)
axes = axes.flatten()

for i, (race, color) in enumerate(zip(races, palette)):
    sns.kdeplot(df_races[df_races['race'] == race]['age'], ax=axes[i], fill=True, color=color)
    axes[i].set_title(f'Age Distribution for Race: {race}')
    axes[i].set_xlabel('Age')
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Density')

for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
    fig.delaxes(axes[j])

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

  • Race A (Asian):

    The density plot for Asians shows a single peak, with the highest density around the late 20s to early 30s. This suggests that most of the police killings within the Asian demographic occur in this age range.

  • Race W (White):

    The distribution for Whites is more spread out compared to Asians, with a peak in the early 30s. There is a noticeable number of killings from the mid-20s to the mid-50s.

  • Race H (Hispanic):

    Hispanics have a peak density in the late 20s.

  • Race B (Black):

    The distribution for Blacks shows a significant peak in the early 20s, suggesting a younger age group is predominantly affected. The density drops off gradually after the peak.

  • Race O (Other):

    The density plot for the 'Other' category also peaks in the late 20s to early 30s.

  • Race N (Native American):

    The Native American plot peaks around the early 30s.
